  "description": "An integral domain is a commutative ring where multiplication behaves the way you expect it to: if the product of two things is zero, then at least one of them must be zero. This property — the absence of zero divisors — is so natural that it takes effort to imagine a ring without it. But such rings exist. In Z/6Z\\mathbb{Z}/6\\mathbb{Z} (the integers modulo 6), 2×3=6≡0(mod6)2 \\times 3 = 6 \\equiv 0 \\pmod{6}, even though neither 2 nor 3 is zero modulo 6. That makes Z/6Z\\mathbb{Z}/6\\mathbb{Z} not an integral domain. The integers Z\\mathbb{Z}, by contrast, are the prototypical integral domain: if ab=0ab = 0 in Z\\mathbb{Z}, then a=0a = 0 or b=0b = 0, period.\n",
  "name": "Integral Domain",
